title: For Sale:  FFL Transfer Service For Your Online or Auction Purchases
postcontent:
Rates and Policies

Firearm Transfer Fee is $15 for 1st transaction, each additional firearm is $10
Transfers for Law Enforcement, Fire Fighters (active or retired) is $10
We accept Visa, Mastercard, Discover, Cash, Money Orders
You should contact us prior to and after purchasing if having a firearm shipped to us.​

Transfer Infomation for local Idaho Customers
Incoming Transfers from a FFL dealer:  We are already listed with most online retailers on their FFL listings, If not I will need to know how they accept a copy of my FFL licence usually either through fax or email, although some dealers require a hardcopy mailed to them. After I send a copy of my FFL licence to the dealer they will ship the firearm to me, I require that the shipping dealer include a copy of their FFL licence and your contact information with the shipment. When the firearm arrives I will contact you and you will need to come to my office to fill out the paperwork.The process is simple, you come in fill out the ATF 4473, present your picture ID or carry permit and I handle all the paperwork, do all the checks required and get you on your way. Generally this process takes no longer than 15 munutes. 

If Purchasing from an Individual
I will send the individual an email with the first 3 and the last 5 digits of my FFL licence, and a link to the ATF web site to verify my shipping address. I will also need the individual to send me a copy of their drivers licence (which must have a physical address on it, no PO boxes). When the firearm arrives I will contact you and you will need to come to my office to fill out the paperwork so we can transfer the firearm to you.
​
Outgoing Transfers
If you have sold a firearm that needs to be shipped out of state it can only be shipped to an FFL. I will need a copy of the FFL's licence, and what type of firearm you are shipping. We generally have shipping boxes for Handguns available at no extra charge, for Long guns you may need to provide a box or there will be a small extra charge for us to buy a box for you.

Important Note on Outgoing Transfers
In the case of firearms shipments there is no law that prevents an individual from shipping a firearm to an FFL holder. Some FFL's do not accept shipments from individuals (We Do), and handguns need to be shipped next day air through shipping companies. The fact that as an FFL we can ship handguns through the USPS, it is sometimes cheaper for you to pay our transfer fee plus the shipping then to ship it yourself. There will also be times where it might be cheaper for you to ship a firearm to an FFL yourself. It depends on the type of firearm, and the distance it is traveling.
Just remember you can only ship a firearm to a Federal Firearms Licensee. When in doubt check the laws or give us a call and we will try to assist you.

Any questions or inquires please feel free to call or email us.

REDACTED
​REDACTED
​Star, Idaho 83669

title: For Trade:  FOR TRADE: BAUER .25ACP POCKET PISTOL (BABY BROWNING COPY)
postcontent:
Bauer .25ACP pocket pistol with one 6 round magazine and about 9 rounds of winchester ammo. Also have 16 pieces of once fired brass and 99 count of Speer Gold Dot hollow point bullets for reloading (should be 100 count but Speer cant count). I Also have a cheap ankle holster to go along with it. Great little gun to conceal in your pocket when a normal concealment holster isn't possible. .25 Auto might seem like a hard caliber to find unless you know where to look. Gander has FMJ, gunbroker.com has both FMJ and HP you can have shipped to an FFL, and local smaller gunshops usual have some Agulia FMJ.

Bauer is an American company that originated in Michigan and made copies of the Baby Browning because importation of the Baby Browning was not allowed at that time and was a very popular pistol in it's day. .25ACP is the smallest centerfire pistol cartridge out today and is more reliable than a .22LR. Great pocket, purse, or vest gun.

Would like to trade for a cheaper used 357 or 38 snub nose.
Double barrel Derringer style pistol in any caliber other than .25 or .32 preferably 9mm
.22LR semi auto or revolver, long barrel, short barrel, hell it could even be pink

title: For Sale:  Kel Tec KSG
postcontent:
For sale is a Black KSG.  We have a small number left with no guarantee that after this one selles, another one will be available. The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".

This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.

 The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.

The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.

Optional accessories shown in the pictures, not included at the price offered.

title: For Sale:  MINI 14
postcontent:
Has one-piece pistol grip stock. The rail system is UTG and is one-piece that comes off easily and is made for a mini, as itslides rigth over the front of the barrel/stock.

The serial numbers start with 186-630xxx indicating that this is the model run from 1991-1999 I believe and this gun was made in 97/98.

Take off the stock and the true "mini" is in incredible shape. The last two pics show the internal front and back of the chamber and I couldn't get my camera to take a decent pic of the inside of the barrel but it is bright, shiny and the rifling is great. The gun shoots perfectly. The action is smooth and crisp. The magazine go in tight and crisp and snaps right into place, where I've had other minis that you fought with the darn thing to get it in there.

The barrel and top of the gun are very very clean and the only blemishes on the thing are a couple nicks on the suppressor and the stock has use marks.

This would be a perfect gun to throw an optic on and use as it is or to take off the stock and rails, sell them, and build whatever you want. I'd put a tactical folding stock on it from tapco or some other brand and just use a regular scope mount with a 3-9x30 myself. Or one could just put a nice red dot on the upper rail of this setup and go.

Anyhow, I hope this better explains the gun. I wish I had the original stock for it, but I don't. The nice thing about these mini's is that there are hundreds of cheap things that can be done to customize them on ebay, amazon and all over. Or if someone wanted a cheap really light mini, take off the rails in about 5 minutes and use the peep sights and go spray some lead at the coyotes.

$500 and thanks for looking. 

Any questions or more pics, call/text (515) 6six4-5nine78. Thanks.

title: For Trade:  Stevens Model 620 take down 12ga pump shotgun 20" riot gun EARLY EARLY serial number
postcontent:
I have a piece of history here. This is a Stevens 620 12ga shotgun designed by John Browning himself. These Stevens with the 20" barrels saw action in WWII and were popular stateside as well. This is an EARLY serial number (under 350) so it's a classic. This one has the much more sought after early buttstock and ribbed forend as well. 

These shotguns easily breakdown into 2 pieces in about 2 seconds with no tools, making them perfect for backpackers, preppers or people transporting them in small car trunks or under truck seats. The finish on the wood on this gun has to be seen. It has that dark, rich, lived-in look. 

You need this gun. I'm only trading it because I have too many guns that I don't shoot. This one is such a classic that I just don't take it out much, but when I do, it's amazing. The action is like butter, or a Swiss watch. Hard to explain but when you rack it you feel the kind of workmanship that is hard to find on today's guns. Also, decades of use have the inner workings nice and worked in for you. The trigger is also crisp and true. 

Anyway, I hate to sell it so I'd rather trade it for something my kid or I will use so take a look at the list below but PLEASE feel free to offer any trades you think of. I'm open to whatever. If you don't have a trade and you absolutely NEED this gun, then shoot me an offer and I might take it, but I'm more in to trading guns than selling them.
